Experiment: Wireless LAN using WDS (Range Extender)
Aim

To configure a Wireless LAN using two Access Points and implement WDS (Wireless Distributed System).

Procedure
Step 1: Reset Router-A

Press the reset button on Router-A for 10–15 seconds.

Step 2: Connect Router-A to PC

Connect the router to PC using LAN cable.

Check IP using command:

ipconfig

Note the Default Gateway (usually 192.168.0.1).

Step 3: Login to Router-A

Open browser.

Type:

http://192.168.0.1

Login using:

Username: admin
Password: admin
Step 4: Configure Wireless Settings

Go to:

Wireless → Basic Settings

Set:

SSID : Router-A

Save the settings.

Step 5: Set Wireless Password

Go to:

Wireless → Wireless Security

Set:

Security Mode : WPA2-PSK
Password : (any 8 characters)

Click Save.

Step 6: Check DHCP Settings

Go to:

DHCP Settings

Verify the IP range:

Start IP : 192.168.0.100
End IP   : 192.168.0.199

Save settings.

Configure Router-B (Range Extender)
Step 7: Reset Router-B

Press reset button for 10–15 seconds.

Step 8: Login to Router-B

Connect Router-B to PC.

Open browser:

http://192.168.0.1

Login with:

admin / admin
Step 9: Change Operation Mode

Go to:

Operation Mode

Select:

Range Extender Mode

Save and reboot.

Step 10: Scan Wireless Networks

Go to:

Wireless → Scan

Click Scan.

List of networks will appear.

Step 11: Connect to Router-A

Select:

SSID : Router-A

Click Connect.

Enter the password of Router-A.

Click Save.

Verification
Step 12: Check IP Address

On PC run:

ipconfig

IP should be in range:

192.168.0.100 – 192.168.0.199
Step 13: Test Connectivity

Run ping command:

ping 192.168.0.102

If reply is received, connection is successful.

Result

Wireless LAN is successfully configured using WDS Range Extender mode.
